  "prompt": "How many units can a 1 MW solar power plant produce in a whole day?",
  "response": "The energy produced by a 1 MW solar power plant in a day depends on several factors, including the average number of sunlight hours, the geographic location, weather conditions, and system efficiency. However, a rough estimate can be provided.\n\nOn average, if a location receives about 4 to 6 hours of effective sunlight per day, a 1 MW solar plant could produce between 4,000 to 6,000 kWh (units) per day. This estimate assumes optimal conditions and efficiency, which can vary. For example:\n\n- If the location has 4 effective sunlight hours per day:  \n  1 MW \u00d7 4 hours = 4,000 kWh per day\n\n- If the location has 6 effective sunlight hours per day:  \n  1 MW \u00d7 6 hours = 6,000 kWh per day\n\nKeep in mind these numbers are estimates and actual production can vary.",
